{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480298"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:40:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:40:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"36"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/36"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.45,0.07,0.17,0.09,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"36"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111655"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/36"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"36"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93725"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11397"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11398"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35164"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39246"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39667"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40140"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40141"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41964"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111655","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111655"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of an itchy rash over his body, particularly affecting his back and arms. He feels very fatigued. He denies any mouth pain or eye symptoms. He has a history of a urinary tract infection diagnosed five days ago, for which he is taking cephalexin. He has no other significant medical history. His medications include paracetamol sustained-release, thyroxine and cephalexin. He is unaware of any unusual chemical exposures and has not changed any topical creams or ointments recently. He has tolerated amoxicillin previously and has no known drug allergies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with a pulse rate of 100/min, blood pressure 120/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. His oral mucosa appears dry but intact, with a crusted lesion noted at the corner of his mouth. Cardiorespiratory examination is unremarkable. His abdomen is soft and non-tender. Neurological examination is normal. Multiple lesions are scattered over his extensor surfaces, posterior trunk, palms and soles (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Erythema multiforme","Hand, foot and mouth disease","Discoid eczema","Stevens-Johnson syndrome","Drug hypersensitivity syndrome"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EErythema multiforme (EM) is an acute hypersensitivity reaction characterised by target lesions. The most common trigger is herpes simplex virus (HSV) infection, followed by \u003Cem\u003EMycoplasma pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E infection. Other triggers include various medications and infections. The crusted lesion on this patient\u0027s lip is likely a herpetic cold sore, which preceded the development of EM. The photograph shows typical target lesions, which are usually less than 3 cm in diameter and have three concentric zones: a dark red inner centre (which may have associated crust or blistering), a middle pale ring due to skin oedema, and an outer brightly erythematous ring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythema multiforme\u003C/strong\u003E typically involves mucosal surfaces in approximately 60% of cases, though this patient denies oral or ocular symptoms. The lesions usually affect less than 10% of total body surface area. EM is self-limiting, with lesions typically resolving over several weeks, though recurrence is possible, particularly with HSV-associated cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStevens-Johnson syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (SJS) can have overlapping features with severe EM, making distinction challenging in some cases. However, SJS typically presents with more severe systemic symptoms, extensive mucosal involvement, and characteristic fragile blistering due to intraepidermal splitting. The blisters in SJS are very fragile and easily rupture, leading to extensive skin denudation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiscoid eczema\u003C/strong\u003E presents as rounded, well-circumscribed inflamed lesions but lacks the characteristic concentric rings seen in EM target lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrug hypersensitivity syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (also known as drug reaction with eosinophilia and systemic symptoms) typically has a longer latency period (2-6 weeks after drug initiation), involves multiple organ systems, and presents with more severe systemic features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHand, foot and mouth disease\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by Coxsackie virus and typically presents with vesicles and ulcers on the palms, soles and in the mouth, rather than the target lesions seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Erythema multiforme is an acute hypersensitivity reaction most commonly triggered by herpes simplex virus infection, followed by Mycoplasma pneumoniae.","Target lesions with three concentric zones are characteristic of erythema multiforme, which typically involves mucosal surfaces in 60% of cases.","Erythema multiforme is self-limiting and resolves over weeks, unlike Stevens-Johnson syndrome which presents with more severe symptoms and fragile blistering."],"references":["Lerch M, Mainetti C, Beretta-Piccoli BT, et al. Current Perspectives on Erythema Multiforme. Clin Rev All Imm. 2018;54:177-84. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29352387/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93725"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"36"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21944"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21944"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/m4e2JRM6Twah3s0AgcVbmM9xbkuQ88.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/m4e2JRM6Twah3s0AgcVbmM9xbkuQ88.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":971}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93725","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93725"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-18T07:50:59+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-18T07:52:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"36"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111655"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":n